\f0\i0\b \ul Quick Configuration
\f1\b0 \ulnone \
First you have to be a registered user of the dynamic DNS service you want to use. If not, you can register at their site (you can generally found the service's URL in the "About DNSUpdate" panel). Note your login name (e.g.: 
\f2\i mylogin
\f1\i0 ) and your password (e.g.: 
\f2\i mypassword
\f1\i0 ) for your service.\
\
Second, you have to register at least one host for this user (e.g.: 
\f2\i myhost.dnsalias.net
\f1\i0 ).\
\
Launch the 
\f0\b DNSUpdate 2
\f1\b0  application. The 
\f0\b DNSUpdate 2
\f1\b0  application has to run 
\f0\b as an Administrator
\f1\b0 !\
If necessary, the application will install the Daemon and the StartupItem (your administrator password will be required) at the right places. The most important part of 
\f0\b DNSUpdate 2
\f1\b0  is the daemon which is automatically launched at boot time, the application 
\f0\b has not to run
\f1\b0  for the client to update, the application is only for installation, configuration and monitoring purposes.\
\
Open the Users Window (File->Edit Users or Command-U).\
\
Create a user (Add User) with your login and password (
\f2\i mylogin
\f1\i0  and 
\f2\i mypassword
\f1\i0 ) and select your service (
\f2\i theservice
\f1\i0 ). The user will appear in the user window as 
\f2\i mylogin
\f1\i0 @
\f2\i theservice
\f1\i0 .\
