\f0\b \cf0 \ul \ulc0 Monitoring DNSUpdate
\f2\i\b0 \
\pard\tx560\tx1120\tx1680\tx2240\tx2800\tx3360\tx3920\tx4480\tx5040\tx5600\tx6160\tx6720\ql\qnatural

\f1\i0 \cf0 \ulnone The 
\f0\b DNSUpdate 2 
\f1\b0 daemon does not need the application anymore to function. It will test the IP every minute (every 15 minutes if the interface is External/External (bypassing Proxy)) and update the dynamic DNS service's database only if needed. However, the 
\f0\b DNSUpdate 2
\f1\b0  application can be used to monitor the daemon activity. It is recommended to monitor the daemon during some (short) time to control that everything is ok with your configuration.\
\
Close the Users Window and open the Monitor Window (Window->Open Monitor Window or Command-O).\
\
With this window, you can control that your IP is registered, the last time it was registered and eventually, if something went wrong, the Status indicates the error (see 
\f2\i Common Errors
\f1\i0  below). If the User is inactive, open the Users Window to check the user status, and eventually reactivate the user.\
\
You can 
\f0\b deactivate
\f1\b0  a host temporary (the daemon will not update it) or 
\f0\b reactivate
\f1\b0  it (if it was deactivated earlier on purpose or because of an error. Be sure that the error is corrected before reactivating the host!). You can also activate or deactivate the hosts with the Users Window.\
\
You can also 
\f0\b pause
\f1\b0  or 
\f0\b start
\f1\b0  the daemon by clicking on the button Pause/Starts daemon. When paused, the daemon will not try to test the interface nor to register your IP.\
\
The information in the User and Last Update columns is adapted to the columns size.\
\
