\f0\b \cf0 \ul \ulc0 Common Errors
\f1\b0 \ulnone \
There was an error while updating your host. The user/host status shows you the problem.\
The main errors are: \
\
- 
\f2\i Bad Auth/Bad Username or Password
\f1\i0 : your login or password is wrong;\
- 
\f2\i No such host
\f1\i0 : the host you entered is not registered by the service;\
- 
\f2\i Not yours/Doesn't belong to this User
\f1\i0 : the host is not yours;\
- 
\f2\i Abuse/Blocked for Abuse
\f1\i0 : your host is blocked. Contact service's support;\
- 
\f2\i Bad domain name
\f1\i0 : you have to provide the full host name (e.g.: "test.dyndns.org" and not "test")\
- The other ones are mainly critical errors (either for the service or 
\f0\b DNSUpdate 2
\f1\b0 ): \
*  dynamic DNS service critical errors (Contact service's support or wait some time): 
\f2\i DNS down
\f1\i0 , 
\f2\i DNS Error
\f1\i0 .\
*  dynamic DNS non critical error: 
\f2\i No Server Answer
\f1\i0  (Time out... maybe the host is temporary unreachable)\
*  The other ones are DNSUpdate critical errors. Contact the author for support (
\f2\i support@dnsupdate.org)
\f1\i0 .\
\
Sometime, maybe, your 
\f0\b Interface
\f1\b0  
\f0\b will be
\f1\b0  
\f0\b inactive
\f1\b0 . There was a problem with your Interface. Maybe you've choosen the wrong (internal) one or, if the interface is external, the daemon had some problems contacting the external server to get your IP (maybe temporarly).\
The Interface will also be inactive if you deconnect from the Internet.\
The daemon will retry automatically and reactivate the Interface when the problems are gone.\
\

\f0\b \ul Unixxxxxxxxx 
\f1\b0 \ulnone \
MacOS X is also a Unix system. I tried to make DNSUpdate as easy to use as possible. I also tried to make DNSUpdate a unix program. For those who are interested, you can do some thing with the 
\f0\b DNSUpdate 2
\f1\b0  within the Terminal.\
The daemon is, in fact, a Unix program which is installed in 
\f2\i /usr/local/sbin
\f1\i0  and is called\'c9 dnsupdate. You can use it to control the daemon. Like the 
\f0\b DNSUpdate 2
\f1\b0  application, it has to run as an administrator to correctly function.\
Here is what you can do with it:\

\f2\i dnsupdate
\f1\i0 : alone gives you a little help for this tool.\

\f2\i dnsupdate pause
\f1\i0 : pauses the daemon.\

\f2\i dnsupdate start
\f1\i0 : starts the daemon.\

\f2\i dnsupdate quit
\f1\i0 : quits the daemon.\

\f2\i dnsupdate daemon
\f1\i0 : launches as a daemon (do not use this unless you know what you are doing!).\

\f2\i dnsupdate magic
\f1\i0 : gives the daemon version (only used for the 
\f0\b DNSUpdate 2
\f1\b0  application for updating purpose)\
When the daemon is launched, it uses two important files: 
\f2\i /var/log/dnsupdate.log
\f1\i0  which log exactly the daemon activity and 
\f2\i /var/run/DNSUpdate_key
\f1\i0  which contains the key to connect to the daemon. Only administrators can access to the content of this last file. It is important for the security of the system.\
\

\f0\b \ul Files
\f1\b0 \ulnone \

\f0\b DNSUpdate 2
\f1\b0  installs different important files on your hard drive:\

\f2\i /Library/LaunchDaemons/org.dnsupdate.daemon.plist
\f1\i0 : the Startup Item used to launch the daemon at boot time.\

\f2\i /Library/Preferences/DNSUpdate
\f1\i0 : the users configuration files.\

\f2\i /usr/local/sbin/dnsupdate
\f1\i0 : the daemon itself.\
/var/log/dnsupdate.log: the daemon log file.\

\f2\i /var/run/DNSUpdate_key
\f1\i0 : the key to connect to the daemon.\

